tools_called.args:
{"action_ids":["3841","3855","3899"],"summary":"Altering mowing regimes on greenspaces and road verges has been shown to affect butterflies and moths. Two studies found that less frequently mown or unmown urban greenspaces had a higher species richness and diversity of butterflies and moths than more frequently mown areas (3841). Unmown public parks and road verges also had a higher abundance of all adult butterflies (3841). One study reported that roadsides mown in late summer had more ringlet butterflies than those mown in mid-summer (3841). Furthermore, road verges mown less frequently or later in the summer had fewer dead butterflies killed by traffic (3841). One study found that scarce copper butterflies more frequently occupied less frequently mown urban grasslands (3841). However, one study found that the management of road verges and land under power lines did not affect butterfly species richness (3841). In the Netherlands, one study noted that butterflies were only recorded on mowed verges where hay was removed (3841).

Regarding herbicide use, one study in the USA found that restored roadside prairies with restricted herbicide application had greater butterfly species richness and abundance and a lower butterfly mortality risk compared to verges dominated by non-native weeds and grasses with no herbicide restrictions (3899). Conversely, a Canadian study found that transmission lines (road verges and power lines) that were not sprayed or mown had a similar species richness of butterflies to those that were sprayed and mown (3899).

For land under power lines, two studies in Finland found that land managed by mechanical cutting had a higher species richness of butterflies than unmanaged land, with the highest richness observed 2-4 years after scrub and tree clearance (3855). One study in Canada, however, found similar butterfly species richness under power lines and on road verges, regardless of whether they were mown once or twice a year, or left unmown (3855). In terms of abundance, one study found that mechanically cut land under power lines had a higher abundance of butterflies than unmanaged land (3855). Another study found that land under power lines and on road verges managed by mowing had a lower abundance of some butterfly species but a similar abundance of others when compared to unmown areas (3855). The time since management also plays a role, with one study finding that chequered skipper abundance was highest in areas cleared within the last two years (3855), and another study noting that pearl-bordered fritillaries used areas where scrub had been cleared one or two years earlier, but not three or more years ago (3855).","query":"What are the effects on butterflies and moths of different methods for managing linear features like road verges and power lines?"}

