  "relevant_summary": "Ceasing mowing on grasslands has shown varied effects on butterfly populations. Two studies found that the butterfly and moth community composition in grasslands abandoned for over 5 years was similar to that in managed grasslands [3957]. However, another study reported that over 6 years of abandonment, the butterfly community became dominated by generalist species [3957]. In terms of species richness, five of seven studies found that grasslands abandoned for 3-20 years had a similar number of butterfly and moth species to mown grasslands [3957]. In contrast, one study found that grasslands abandoned for more than 50 years had lower butterfly species richness [3957]. The abundance of butterflies also showed mixed results, with some studies finding a lower abundance of certain butterfly species in grasslands abandoned for over a year [3957], while others found a higher abundance of all butterflies in grasslands left uncut for a summer [3957]. Some studies also noted a shift in community composition, with an increase in woodland and hedgerow butterfly species but a decrease in grassland species in abandoned meadows [3957].\n\nSimilarly, the cessation of grazing on grasslands has led to a range of outcomes for butterflies. Two studies found that the butterfly and moth community composition in grasslands abandoned for more than 5 years was similar to that in grazed grasslands [3956]. However, another study observed that after 6 years of abandonment, the butterfly community was dominated by generalist species [3956]. Butterfly species richness in abandoned grasslands was found to be similar to grazed grasslands in six of nine studies [3956], while some studies found lower richness [3956] and others found higher richness in abandoned grasslands [3956]. One study also found that species richness was highest in grasslands where grazing had ceased for 2-9 years compared to those abandoned for longer or those currently being grazed [3956]. Butterfly abundance also varied, with some studies reporting higher numbers in abandoned grasslands [3956], while others found lower [3956] or similar numbers [3956]. Additionally, some studies found that an increase in woodland and hedgerow butterflies was accompanied by a decrease in grassland species, with the extinction of some species in abandoned meadows [3956]. A review in Europe noted that ceasing grazing benefited six out of 67 butterfly species of conservation concern [3956].",
