  "relevant_summary": "Abandoning management on grasslands can have both positive and negative effects on butterfly and moth populations. \n\nPotential negative consequences of abandoning management include the extinction of six heath fritillary populations on unmanaged grasslands (3966). In contrast, traditional hay meadows mown once a year supported a higher abundance of heath fritillary adults and caterpillars than old, abandoned meadows (3908). Summer-grazed or mown grasslands were found to have a lower abundance of woodland butterflies and burnet moths than abandoned grasslands (3908). Additionally, after a reduction in management, the abundance of two butterfly species decreased, and 12 species of moth showed a preference for more intensively managed grasslands (3958).\n\nPotential benefits of abandoning or reducing management intensity on grasslands include a higher species richness of butterflies and moths (3958). Less intensively managed grasslands may also support more specialist moth species, species of conservation concern, and butterfly species with specific host plant requirements (3958). Several studies found that the abundance of butterflies, micro-moths, and declining macro-moths was higher in low-input or unfertilized, ungrazed grasslands (3958). One study found that butterflies were less abundant in managed grasslands compared to unmanaged ones (3908). Similarly, unmown grasslands were found to have a higher abundance and species richness of nocturnal moths compared to mown grasslands (3908). Some species, like the small pearl-bordered fritillary, were found more frequently in abandoned meadows than in grazed ones (3908).\n\nSome studies found no significant difference, with the species richness and community composition of butterflies and moths being similar between managed and unmanaged or less-intensively managed grasslands (3958, 3908).",
